richTextContent.insert: Fixing broken Apex code is the most direct way to reduce emissions. Repeat executions are more likely as users try to circumvent any errors.
Addressing the items on the right will improve user experience and system stability as well as reducing emissions.

This dashboard shows the estimated carbon emissions of Salesforce App Server CPU time via specific features and products. The dashboard does not calculate the entire carbon emissions footprint of an org. Learn more about how this dashboard works and how to use it [here]
Use the slider above to select a target run time for synchronous apex.  Salesforce's best practice is for synchronous Apex to execute in under 5 seconds.

The lower the slider, the better the user experience, and more Apex methods will come into scope for optimisation.  Use the table on the right to find classes and methods that take longer to run than the target run time and apply Apex Design Best Practices.

Use the slider above to see reports that take longer to run than the threshold you selected. Faster running reports offer a better user experience and are likely to generate less carbon per execution. Ideally, reports should take less than 5 seconds to run. You can decrease the carbon emissions associated with reports by improving their performance.
Asynchronous Apex does not have to follow the 5-second rule as synchronous Apex. Moving logic to Batch, Scheduled and Queued jobs is encouraged in order to avoid hitting execution governor limits.
However, any particular method that is generating large volumes of carbon should be subjected to the same Apex design and optimisaiton best practices.
